Anonymous Wed 31 Mar 2021 15:30:06 No.37542896 Report
Quoted By: >>37545161
>>37538625
>>37539070

There are two characters in a story I once scripted out that follow something similar with that kind of dark direction. Two powerful beings infatuated with each other bind themselves to immortality, and also to be compelled to seek out the other wherever they might be. That second part was put into the deal without the knowledge of the other. This on top of his general moral decay over time causes the female to start to resent him and try to depart, only to be drawn back over and over. The anger and spite caused by her attempts drives him to turn their relationship into a device for torment as punishment, causing a spiral into mutual hatred and abuse that never ends because they can never separate in any way. Eventually she figures out a way to wipe his memory during reincarnation and thoughtlessly uses it, wiping his memories and personality completely. But this also removes whatever knowledge he had of how to remove their binding.
So the story would be about their journey to figure out a way to sever this, while they're stuck in this twisted dark pairing where the roles of abuser become switched as the female who is now rotten to the core by hundreds of years of this curse frequently torments the male with constantly badgering, and destroying the few things he discovers happiness in, despite him now effectively being a different person.
There's a pivotal moment later in the story, at a point where her efforts are starting to twist the male into something resembling what he once was, where they find out something that implies they've been through all this before. The memory wiping which might not have been done by her last time and might've been mutual, and the journey to find solutions that might not even still exist anymore, and it's likely this has been repeating for thousands of years. This revelation shellshocks both of them... and that's where I kinda fell out of writing this because I didn't know where to go from there.

>>37550781
>Probably elements of hmofa but I'm not exactly sure yet
I would absolutely recommend you sit down and think about gameplay first. For your first game, knowing the scope is crucial. Don't aim too high and don't get lost in presentation (graphics, GUI, etc.) before you actually have something to present (the gameplay). I made tons of simple prototypes just to get a handle of things and to work through ideas before I finally settled on one I wanted to make. Now that I'm in a more serious development stage I'm glad I have all of that to draw from, because there's a lot of smaller things you might not expect, but that can really trip you up if you're not careful

Forgot: most importantly, don't get hung up on trying to "learn". https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=6avJHaC3C2U
Not super edifying, but fascinating, a good hype piece, and died give you a pretty good overview of the basic modes of thinking involved in programming. I'd also recommend brushing up on a little trig if you haven't recently because trig is super useful in game design specifically. I don't mean to suggest you should put the project on hold to practice math, but when you find yourself asking "how do I make X move in pattern Y" or "how do I measure the way X is moving in pattern Y" trig is going to be your answer like 7 times out of 10. It's usually going to be basic bitch trig though. I find I do a LOT of arithmetic, a good amount of trig and geometry, a bit of algebra, and a touch of calculus
